# 9.1 General

## 9.1.1 Definition

Coordination is the exchange of information and transfer of responsibility between Air Traffic Control units.

The Approach Controller shall ensure that coordination is clear, timely, and unambiguous at all times.

---

## 9.1.2 Objectives

The Approach Controller shall:

- Ensure safe separation between aircraft  
- Facilitate smooth transfer of traffic between units  
- Prevent conflicting clearances  
- Maintain efficient traffic flow  

---

## 9.1.3 Types of Coordination

Coordination may be conducted by:

- **Verbal (voice communication)** – primary method  
- **System-based coordination (handoff tools)**  
- **Pre-defined procedures (LOAs / SOPs)**  

All coordination shall be explicit and clearly understood.

---

## 9.1.4 Transfer of Communication

The Approach Controller shall:

- Transfer aircraft to the next unit at the appropriate time  
- Ensure correct frequency is issued  
- Avoid late or premature transfer  

Communication transfer does not transfer control responsibility.

---

## 9.1.5 Transfer of Control

Transfer of control occurs when:

- The receiving controller accepts the aircraft, or  
- As defined by local procedures  

The transferring controller shall remain responsible until transfer of control is complete.

---

## 9.1.6 Positive Coordination

The Approach Controller shall:

- Obtain explicit agreement when required  
- Avoid assumptions regarding coordination  
- Confirm all critical information  

Positive coordination ensures both controllers have a shared understanding of the situation.

---

## 9.1.7 Responsibility

The transferring controller remains responsible for the aircraft until:

- Transfer of control is completed, and  
- The receiving controller has accepted responsibility  

Responsibility shall not be assumed without confirmation.

---

## 9.1.8 Limitations

The Approach Controller shall not:

- Assume coordination has occurred without confirmation  
- Transfer aircraft without ensuring the receiving unit is prepared  
- Issue clearances that conflict with adjacent units  

---

## 9.1.9 Key Principle

Effective coordination is based on clarity, confirmation, and standardisation.

The Approach Controller shall:

- Communicate clearly  
- Confirm critical actions  
- Maintain shared situational awareness  

Assumptions shall never replace coordination.

---
